tags: just be nice to my dotter...
SHE HAS BEEN THROUGH A LOT OK?!
AIN'T NOBODY FUCKS WITH MY BABY!
summary:
lostlittlesatellites replied to your post  Tbh it’s not out of malicious intent and I won’t even say it’s bad 
writing or plot...
body:
lostlittlesatellites replied to your post

Tbh it’s not out of malicious intent and I won’t even say it’s bad writing or plot convenience (although it is a bit of the latter). It comes down to Jon’s line in the next ep “We need to trust each other”, which becomes a theme in their dynamic. It’s not bc Sansa wanted Jon to die or to blindside him but bc LF raised her doubts about who she can trust and putting herself in Jon’s hands after so many people (especially men and even family - Lysa) have betrayed her or have failed to protect her.

And it becomes a running theme for BOTH of them learning to trust each other bc they didn’t have that relationship before. And a lot of it stems out of previous insecurities and fears. People just add the worst reason to it. She doesn’t want power but she fears being in a position of little agency or under a man bc of her experiences.

But ofc there’s other factors: not knowing if LF would come at all or not thinking Jon would want to use LF as an ally. Maybe out of a sense of shame of what Jon would think of her if she asked. There’s plenty reasons tbh. And I don’t get why people assume it has to be the worst when she clearly has a lot of issues and does seem to have an affection for Jon. Its perhaps only around him that she’s been the most genuinely happy since she left WF.

A lot of this gets to the heart of one relevant point that always really ~grinds my gears~ when this is discussed: people seem to want to view Sansa having trust issues as some kind of deep character flaw. It’s not. She’s a rape victim, she is an abuse victim, she is a torture victim… People who have experienced those things are going to have trust issues.

I mean, let’s flip it around: if it were Jon who maybe wasn’t completely up front with Sansa or kept things from her, would we be judging him so harshly? I would be willing to bet my left boob we wouldn’t. Why? Because he was betrayed by men who were supposed to be his brothers? They murdered him. He granted all of them his trust; even men like Janos Slynt who he didn’t like and who, in hindsight, he probably shouldn’t have trusted. They betrayed that trust and (literally) stabbed him in the back. No one could blame him for being wary, even of people who are supposed to be his allies.

Likewise, Sansa has been betrayed by almost everyone she has come across who claimed to care about her and have her best interests at heart. Cersei, Joffrey, Petyr, they Tyrells, even Lysa who was (like Jon) her own family. The King’s Guard, who were supposed to be the most noble and trust worthy True Knights in the Seven Kingdoms stripped her down, beat her up, and tormented her in open court for everyone to see. Even Theon, who ended up saving her life, betrayed her in the beginning by telling Ramsay of her plan with Brienne. There seems to be this overarching suspicion that Sansa not fully trusting Jon is about Jon. Again, it’s not; it’s not any kind of negative reflection on Jon or her relationship with him at all really. It’s because of a lifetime’s worth of tragic experience that has made her unable to completely trust anyone. In fact, Jon is probably one of the first people in a darn long hecking time that she has felt comfortable letting her guard down around.

I never understand why people seem to be so critical of Sansa having trust issues when she has been amply shown, time and time again, that people cannot be trusted. One of the most heartbreaking Sansa quotes imo is from ACoK: “Once she had loved Prince Joffrey with all her heart, and admired and trusted his mother, the queen. They had repaid that love and trust with her father’s head. Sansa would never make that mistake again.” From very early on, that is her head space, trust no one.   

Sansa has been put through so much at the hands of others and put in so many situations where she had no control. She’s still learning, she’s still growing, and most importantly, she’s still healing.

summary: Can we just accept that the younger and more beautiful queen in Cersei’s prophecy is Sansa? The way I always read it is that...
body: Can we just accept that the younger and more beautiful queen in Cersei’s prophecy is Sansa? The way I always read it is that it’s supposed to be ironic that Cersei envies young and pretty girls she comes across because she’s always had the prettiest face, whereas Sansa’s true beauty is on the inside (Margaery? Daenerys? nah) - something that Cersei doesn’t register or deems to be a weakness.
